if you think about it.

00:13:51.810 --> 00:13:54.960
If you plow in heavy
clay soil, you're only

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:57.230
gonna be able to plow a little bit.

00:13:57.230 --> 00:13:59.880
If you're plowing in light sandy soils,

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:03.200
you're gonna plow a lot,
so an acre which is a day's

00:14:03.200 --> 00:14:06.600
worth of work for a plow
team, varied from one place

00:14:06.600 --> 00:14:10.739
to another, that irregularity
is what characterizes

00:14:10.739 --> 00:14:13.890
preindustrial time or preindustrial work.

00:14:13.890 --> 00:14:17.470
It's not divided by time,
it's divided by the tasks

00:14:17.470 --> 00:14:18.960
you have to do.

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:22.200
And there's no real division
between life and leisure,

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:24.730
work and things that you need to do,

00:14:24.730 --> 00:14:26.760
it's irregular and that
kind of irregularity

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:29.370
dominates the way in which people live.

00:14:29.370 --> 00:14:31.500
Villages were organized around churches,

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:33.609
the church bell rang, the morning rang,

00:14:33.609 --> 00:14:36.020
the evening rang when
you had to go to Mass,

00:14:36.020 --> 00:14:39.560
didn't tell time, didn't
have any timekeeping as such.

00:14:39.560 --> 00:14:42.950
You had the sun, you had
the cock crow and you had

00:14:42.950 --> 00:14:44.710
basically your work and that was the way

00:14:44.710 --> 00:14:46.900
in which the rhythms of life were set.

00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:51.370
Sunrise, sunset, and the various
seasons that went with it.

00:14:51.370 --> 00:14:54.750
The calendar, the annual
calendar was likewise dominated

00:14:54.750 --> 00:14:57.970
by the rhythms of agriculture,
the rhythms of what you did

00:14:57.970 --> 00:15:02.970
daily, sowing, reaping,
hoeing, harvest or it could be

00:15:05.030 --> 00:15:09.380
pasturing, lambing, shearing, butchering

00:15:09.380 --> 00:15:11.940
and all the things that you
did in the pasture world,

00:15:11.940 --> 00:15:14.100
but those were the activities,
the kinds of things you did

00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:16.480
and that's how you told
time, you told the seasons

00:15:16.480 --> 00:15:19.883
according to what you had to
do when you needed to do them.

00:15:20.795 --> 00:15:24.300
On top of that, there were
also and most people thought

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:27.100
about not just the tasks they
had to do or the seasons,

00:15:27.100 --> 00:15:31.010
but they also thought greatly
about the Christian calendar,

00:15:31.010 --> 00:15:35.090
the feast days, time was
marked by great feasts,

00:15:35.090 --> 00:15:37.270
not feasts in the sense of a lot of food,

00:15:37.270 --> 00:15:40.100
but celebrations of
saints, Saint Bartholomew,

00:15:40.100 --> 00:15:41.690
you'll hear about, Saint Martin.

00:15:41.690 --> 00:15:45.459
We only have left pretty
much Christmas and Easter

00:15:45.459 --> 00:15:49.530
from those times, but
every week had, every day

00:15:49.530 --> 00:15:52.180
had a saint associated
with it and we'll see,

00:15:52.180 --> 00:15:54.340
that's how they told time.

00:15:54.340 --> 00:15:57.630
So work, life, feast days,
that's what structured

00:15:57.630 --> 00:16:01.010
people's memory, that's how
they came to locate themselves

00:16:01.010 --> 00:16:03.850
in time, historical time if you will,

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:06.120
so I want to illustrate
that by some quotes

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:09.630
which we don't, one of the
problems of doing preindustrial

00:16:09.630 --> 00:16:11.820
work is that the people
didn't write anything,

00:16:11.820 --> 00:16:13.835
they didn't leave diaries,
they didn't write letters

00:16:13.835 --> 00:16:16.780
so we have to kind of
triangulate and get at them

00:16:16.780 --> 00:16:18.947
from other ways what
they were thinking about,

00:16:18.947 --> 00:16:20.221
what was going on in their minds

00:16:20.221 --> 00:16:21.767
and one of the ways we get in their minds

00:16:21.767 --> 00:16:23.189
was in England,

00:16:23.189 --> 00:16:25.730
coming of age was a very important time.

00:16:25.730 --> 00:16:27.710
You came of age if you were a man at 21,

00:16:27.710 --> 00:16:30.240
a woman at 14 or 15.

00:16:30.240 --> 00:16:31.810
And that was important
because at those ages

00:16:31.810 --> 00:16:34.780
you could inherit land and
the king was very concerned

00:16:34.780 --> 00:16:37.890
about that, who was gonna
inherit land that belonged to him

00:16:37.890 --> 00:16:42.130
and so he had a whole system
set up called proof of age,

00:16:42.130 --> 00:16:44.350
so if you think you're 21 years old,

00:16:44.350 --> 00:16:48.160
the king would set up an
inquest, which was a jury,

00:16:48.160 --> 00:16:50.780
and the local neighbors, 12
of them, would get together

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:52.540
and testify as to whether or not

00:16:52.540 --> 00:16:54.260
you were really 12 years old

00:16:54.260 --> 00:16:56.517
or you were 15 years
old or whatever it was

00:16:56.517 --> 00:16:58.670
and so we have records of that that say,

00:16:58.670 --> 00:17:01.650
these proof of ages, and you'll see that

00:17:01.650 --> 00:17:02.960
they're not exactly what you think.

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:05.700
So I've got one and fortunately
there were two juries,

00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:08.540
two inquests, that were
held three months apart,

00:17:08.540 --> 00:17:13.540
one in October of 1303 and
one in January of 1305.

