00:21:03.740 --> 00:21:06.010
widower for 21 years.

00:21:06.010 --> 00:21:07.863
In the second January,

00:21:08.744 --> 00:21:12.150
he agreed that Emma was 15
years old because he recollected

00:21:12.150 --> 00:21:15.870
that his wife Annabelle died
12 years ago at Christmas

00:21:15.870 --> 00:21:19.840
last and on Sunday before the
Feast of Saint Peter Cathedral

00:21:19.840 --> 00:21:22.690
following, the said Emma
was three years of age.

00:21:22.690 --> 00:21:26.320
Now Elias was actually in the jury in 1295

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:29.310
that testified that she was
three years old in 1295,

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:32.180
but he says no, she's 15 years old,

00:21:32.180 --> 00:21:34.740
so the point here is that this
is kind of a little window

00:21:34.740 --> 00:21:37.446
you can have onto the way
in which people thought.

00:21:37.446 --> 00:21:40.640
We all look at our watches,
we look at our time

00:21:40.640 --> 00:21:43.720
and gradually as these
jurors were talking,

00:21:43.720 --> 00:21:47.490
time was changing, they
were establishing work bells

00:21:47.490 --> 00:21:50.470
in cities to get cloth
workers to work and appear

00:21:50.470 --> 00:21:52.380
on time and when they
could take meals and when

00:21:52.380 --> 00:21:54.590
they could go home, a
very small proportion

00:21:54.590 --> 00:21:57.090
of the population, but
that's the start of it.

00:21:57.090 --> 00:22:00.180
From work bells you get clocks in towns

00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:02.620
and clocks tell the workers in the towns,

00:22:02.620 --> 00:22:04.760
the cloth workers, the leather workers,

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:07.080
the beer makers, the beer brewers,

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:09.270
and all of those people when they can work

00:22:09.270 --> 00:22:10.760
and when they can leave
work, when they can eat

00:22:10.760 --> 00:22:12.980
and when they can stop
eating, then you start getting

00:22:12.980 --> 00:22:15.680
clocks in homes and clocks in shops,

00:22:15.680 --> 00:22:17.680
then those clocks get
transported to your wrists

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:20.180
or your pocket, actually,
first, you carry a clock

00:22:20.180 --> 00:22:24.320
in your pocket and those
things tell you what time it is

00:22:24.320 --> 00:22:27.740
but they also tell you what
your work is supposed to do

00:22:27.740 --> 00:22:30.060
and it's the work that regulates the time,

00:22:30.060 --> 00:22:33.570
it's the work that regulates
your life so that you think

00:22:33.570 --> 00:22:36.760
not in terms of oh, this
task is gonna take so long,

00:22:36.760 --> 00:22:39.210
it says I have so much
time to do this task

00:22:39.210 --> 00:22:41.975
and suddenly time becomes a commodity.

00:22:41.975 --> 00:22:45.320
You can save time, you can spend time,

00:22:45.320 --> 00:22:48.410
you can waste time, that
wouldn't have made any sense

00:22:48.410 --> 00:22:50.720
to Elias de Stretton or
any of his colleagues

00:22:50.720 --> 00:22:53.570
at that time, the
apotheosis of this, I think,

00:22:53.570 --> 00:22:58.570
is the FitBit, not only
does it calibrate minutes,

00:22:59.525 --> 00:23:04.460
seconds, miniseconds, it
also calibrates heartbeats,

00:23:04.460 --> 00:23:07.230
sleeping rhythms, brain waves,

00:23:07.230 --> 00:23:08.726
so there's no part of your life

00:23:08.726 --> 00:23:11.470
which is without regulation
and without the discipline

00:23:11.470 --> 00:23:15.110
of time, it's that discipline
of time that's taken

00:23:15.110 --> 00:23:18.652
centuries to impose,
those medieval villagers

00:23:18.652 --> 00:23:21.420
resisted and resisted and resisted

00:23:21.420 --> 00:23:23.780
and the history of
industrialization in the West

00:23:23.780 --> 00:23:26.919
and in Europe is the history
not only of the imposition

00:23:26.919 --> 00:23:29.998
of time but the resistance
of time, thank you.

