00:24:01.490 --> 00:24:05.570
Premodern Muslims, it's fair
to say, were obsessively

00:24:05.570 --> 00:24:08.070
and deeply engaged with time.

00:24:08.070 --> 00:24:12.610
So you might find a philosopher
in 11th century Baghdad

00:24:12.610 --> 00:24:16.000
who thought about the
relationship between God

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.880
and eternity, you might have a

00:24:20.900 --> 00:24:25.900
11th or 12th century Persian
scientist and inventor

00:24:25.960 --> 00:24:30.302
who spent lots of his,
who spent a lot of time

00:24:30.302 --> 00:24:34.570
designing and building the best clocks

00:24:34.570 --> 00:24:37.100
and astrolabes of his era.

00:24:37.100 --> 00:24:41.170
And a 13th century
Anatolian mystic who tried

00:24:41.170 --> 00:24:46.170
through his meditations to
transcend time altogether.

00:24:46.180 --> 00:24:50.570
So in all of these sort of
deep engagements with time,

00:24:50.570 --> 00:24:55.320
with defining it, with
pondering its philosophical

00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:57.683
implications, with measuring it,

00:24:59.106 --> 00:25:02.100
you see sort of engagement
across a range of disciplines

00:25:02.100 --> 00:25:06.520
in Islamic studies, so to
talk in any serious way

00:25:06.520 --> 00:25:10.570
about time in Islam is to
engage with art, art history,

00:25:10.570 --> 00:25:12.700
history of science, Koranic studies,

00:25:12.700 --> 00:25:15.900
philosophy, theology,
and the list goes on.

00:25:15.900 --> 00:25:18.390
So what I'm gonna do
today is confine myself

00:25:18.390 --> 00:25:21.390
to four areas, I'm gonna
highlight intersections

00:25:21.390 --> 00:25:24.060
in terms of the study of the Koran,

00:25:24.060 --> 00:25:26.455
cosmology, some cosmology,

00:25:26.455 --> 00:25:30.660
history of science,
philosophy and mysticism,

