we follow a solar calendar,

00:28:05.610 --> 00:28:07.480
for us in the northern hemisphere,

00:28:07.480 --> 00:28:10.130
January is always a winter month,

00:28:10.130 --> 00:28:12.550
it was when I was young, it is now

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:15.706
and it will be when I am very, very old.

00:28:15.706 --> 00:28:18.130
Islam instituted a lunar calendar,

00:28:18.130 --> 00:28:23.080
and it's roughly 11 days
shorter than the solar calendar.

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:27.560
And what that means,
essentially, is that the calendar

00:28:27.560 --> 00:28:31.896
is completely detached or
unmoored from the seasons

00:28:31.896 --> 00:28:34.770
so let's take the example of Ramadan.

00:28:34.770 --> 00:28:37.300
The holy month of fasting in Islam,

00:28:37.300 --> 00:28:40.403
when Muslims fast from sunup to sundown.

00:28:41.956 --> 00:28:45.960
In my youth, Ramadan was in the fall,

00:28:45.960 --> 00:28:47.750
right, when the days
are shorter so the time

00:28:47.750 --> 00:28:49.880
that you have to fast is a lot shorter

00:28:50.870 --> 00:28:54.566
and now that I am 20, (laughs)

00:28:54.566 --> 00:28:56.133
(audience laughs)

00:28:56.133 --> 00:28:59.350
I won't say how old I am,
Ramadan is in the summer months

00:28:59.350 --> 00:29:03.040
when the days are a lot longer and so

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:07.680
Muslims might fast something
like 16 hours, 17 hours

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:11.960
of the day, in addition to
this calendrical innovation

00:29:11.960 --> 00:29:13.033
or change,

00:29:14.990 --> 00:29:17.810
there were a whole host
of new rituals that were

00:29:17.810 --> 00:29:20.510
associated with the
religion, so one of them

00:29:20.510 --> 00:29:23.950
is the five daily prayers,
which were set at,

00:29:23.950 --> 00:29:27.730
which are recited at set times of the day,

00:29:27.730 --> 00:29:31.100
and they are also recited with a believer

00:29:31.100 --> 00:29:34.390
facing the Kaaba, which
is in the city of Mecca

00:29:34.390 --> 00:29:37.200
in Saudi Arabia, the
sacred center of Islam

00:29:37.200 --> 00:29:40.870
and the introduction
of all of these rituals

00:29:40.870 --> 00:29:45.370
was against the backdrop of
tremendous Muslim expansion,

00:29:45.370 --> 00:29:48.940
from the 8th to the 16th
century, the Muslim world

00:29:48.940 --> 00:29:53.040
expanded or grew out of its
boundaries in Central Arabia.

00:29:53.040 --> 00:29:55.080
In the West, it went all the way to Spain,

00:29:55.080 --> 00:29:59.553
in the east, to the borders of
China and so this historical

00:30:01.010 --> 00:30:04.270
moment or these eras,
let's say, were accompanied

00:30:04.270 --> 00:30:08.660
by tremendous advances in
sciences and technology,

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:13.170
the need to navigate across
this incredible expanse of land

00:30:13.170 --> 00:30:14.700
and then for a believer,

00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:17.940
wherever they were, to have
to figure what the time

00:30:17.940 --> 00:30:20.500
of prayer is, when it is,
and how you figure out

00:30:20.500 --> 00:30:25.290
where Mecca was or is, resulted
in sort of different types

00:30:25.290 --> 00:30:27.873
of advances in astronomy
and you heard last week

00:30:27.873 --> 00:30:30.852
that astronomy in the
premodern period was the queen

00:30:30.852 --> 00:30:35.852
of sciences, so from about
the ninth to the 16th century,

00:30:35.880 --> 00:30:40.683
Muslims were actually leaders
in the area of astronomy.

00:30:41.530 --> 00:30:45.696
There are incredible astrolabes and clocks

00:30:45.696 --> 00:30:50.490
that were invented in this
time that just testify to

00:30:50.490 --> 00:30:53.827
the Muslim preoccupation with
astronomy, with technological

00:30:53.827 --> 00:30:58.560
advancement and also with
absorbing a whole host of

00:30:58.560 --> 00:31:02.203
cultural influences as Islam expanded.

00:31:03.949 --> 00:31:07.440
One of these people was the polymath

00:31:07.440 --> 00:31:09.230
Al Jezari Ibn al Razzaz,

00:31:09.230 --> 00:31:12.080
Al Jezari, who wrote this marvelous book

00:31:12.080 --> 00:31:14.830
that has been recently
translated from Arabic

00:31:14.830 --> 00:31:17.660
into English, the Book
of Knowledge of Ingenious

00:31:17.660 --> 00:31:22.320
Mechanical Devices, and
there are sketches in there

00:31:22.320 --> 00:31:25.510
and plans for all sorts
of incredible devices,

00:31:25.510 --> 00:31:28.488
that employed technologies that were

00:31:28.488 --> 00:31:33.058
really advanced for that
time, in the 13th century,

00:31:33.058 --> 00:31:36.910
12th and 13th century and
one of these ingenious

00:31:36.910 --> 00:31:40.683
mechanical devices was this
awesome elephant clock.

00:31:41.570 --> 00:31:44.400
It's also called the water
castle clock and it has been

00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:47.990
reconstructed in a mall in
Abu Dhabi, in all places,

00:31:47.990 --> 00:31:51.254
so if you're ever there,
you can go see how it works.

00:31:51.254 --> 00:31:53.690
But you can see from the
clock that it incorporates

00:31:53.690 --> 00:31:56.260
a number of artistic
influences from across

00:31:56.260 --> 00:32:00.740
the Muslim world, there's
allusions to East Asian art,

00:32:00.740 --> 00:32:04.070
and other geographic
regions of the Muslim world

00:32:04.070 --> 00:32:07.680
and I have this very short
video because I am not

00:32:07.680 --> 00:32:11.300
an engineer or a scientist,
I do Islamic studies

00:32:11.300 --> 00:32:13.227
and history, I wouldn't
be able to describe to you

00:32:13.227 --> 00:32:15.790
how this clock works if
