00:33:28.690 --> 00:33:32.420
I mean, and there were
other clocks like this.

00:33:32.420 --> 00:33:35.640
Across the Muslim world,
actually, and you can get

00:33:35.640 --> 00:33:39.150
a sense of how these were
not just mechanical devices

00:33:39.150 --> 00:33:42.310
meant to tell time, they
were the celebration

00:33:42.310 --> 00:33:46.420
of a cosmopolitan global
culture, they had an obsession

00:33:46.420 --> 00:33:49.290
with precision, with
technological advancement

00:33:49.290 --> 00:33:53.390
and with incorporating all
kinds of artistic influences.

00:33:53.390 --> 00:33:55.640
Now in addition to these what I would say

00:33:55.640 --> 00:34:00.280
are practical somewhat mundane
concerns of keeping time,

00:34:00.280 --> 00:34:03.440
there were other Muslims who
grappled with more abstract

00:34:03.440 --> 00:34:08.440
problems, 9th and 10th century, oh, no.

00:34:08.759 --> 00:34:13.380
9th and 10th century Muslims
engaged with the ideas

00:34:13.380 --> 00:34:18.010
of Aristotle and other Greek
philosophers who maintained

00:34:18.010 --> 00:34:20.870
that the world is eternal.

00:34:20.870 --> 00:34:23.528
Now this idea actually doesn't sit

00:34:23.528 --> 00:34:26.200
quite well, it's not really compatible

00:34:26.200 --> 00:34:29.130
with the notion of creation of a cosmos

00:34:29.130 --> 00:34:32.373
at a fixed moment in
time by a creator God.

00:34:33.690 --> 00:34:36.060
Muslims at the time who engaged with

00:34:36.060 --> 00:34:38.400
the Hellenic tradition
were really impressed

00:34:38.400 --> 00:34:41.030
with the Hellenic tradition,
they considered Aristotle

00:34:41.030 --> 00:34:44.880
to be actually somewhat
of a Muslim philosopher,

00:34:44.880 --> 00:34:48.450
if you will, and they tried
to integrate his thought

00:34:48.450 --> 00:34:53.070
into Muslim thought and
philosophers like Avicenna,

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:56.510
Ibn al Arabi, articulated
a whole host of questions

00:34:56.510 --> 00:35:00.890
and analytical frameworks
for trying to reconcile

00:35:00.890 --> 00:35:03.610
Greek and Islamic
philosophy and they asked

00:35:03.610 --> 00:35:07.540
all sorts of questions, I've
listed a few of them here.

00:35:07.540 --> 00:35:11.977
Like what is eternity,
did it exist before God,

00:35:11.977 --> 00:35:16.977
did God create time, does
time exist separate from God?

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:20.840
As an aspect of his creation,
and obviously I am not

00:35:20.840 --> 00:35:24.367
going to talk about those
philosophical discourses here,

00:35:24.367 --> 00:35:29.160
but I just wanted to sort
of highlight that this area

00:35:29.160 --> 00:35:31.490
that is time and the
philosophical tradition

00:35:31.490 --> 00:35:33.620
and the Muslim philosophical tradition

00:35:33.620 --> 00:35:36.680
is a wonderful way to
explore the shared histories

00:35:36.680 --> 00:35:40.750
and interconnectedness of
Greek and Islamic philosophy.

00:35:40.750 --> 00:35:44.050
And I will just say in brief
that one of the solutions

00:35:44.050 --> 00:35:46.990
that Muslim philosophers
put forth was that time

00:35:46.990 --> 00:35:51.780
was indeed an attribute
of God, a divine attribute

00:35:51.780 --> 00:35:55.870
like mercy and reason, they
enumerated a whole host

00:35:55.870 --> 00:35:58.540
of attributes that were divine attributes

00:35:58.540 --> 00:36:03.423
and time became one of
them, so obviously for some

00:36:05.370 --> 00:36:08.510
Muslim philosophers and
theologians in particular,

00:36:08.510 --> 00:36:11.990
concepts and questions of
time were to be tackled

00:36:11.990 --> 00:36:15.050
through intellectual or mental exertion.

00:36:15.050 --> 00:36:16.880
For the last group that I'll talk about,

00:36:16.880 --> 00:36:20.240
Muslim mystics, also known as Sufis,

00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:23.362
they took an entirely different angle.

00:36:23.362 --> 00:36:28.362
For Sufis, time was an
experiential challenge,

00:36:28.670 --> 00:36:32.710
not an intellectual one,
through rituals that involved

00:36:32.710 --> 00:36:37.710
music and dance, Sufis actually
tried to embody eternity

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:41.680
so I'll give a very
brief explanation here.

00:36:41.680 --> 00:36:45.230
In Muslim thought, right,
the creation of Adam

00:36:45.230 --> 00:36:49.610
and all of humankind after
him represents what we call

00:36:49.610 --> 00:36:52.530
the moment of a primordial covenant

00:36:52.530 --> 00:36:56.630
with God, it was a moment
when humanity attested to

00:36:56.630 --> 00:37:00.050
or submitted to divine will
and was in perfect harmony

00:37:00.050 --> 00:37:04.270
with it, right, so Sufis
through their rituals

00:37:04.270 --> 00:37:09.270
tried to return to that
moment of perfect harmony

00:37:09.580 --> 00:37:12.860
or union with the divine
and they do this through

00:37:12.860 --> 00:37:15.800
a whole host of meditations,
some are just invocations

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:18.350
that are recited, some are dances,

00:37:18.350 --> 00:37:23.350
and one of the most well
known of these Sufi groups

00:37:23.440 --> 00:37:27.730
is that associated with Rumi,
the internationally acclaimed

00:37:27.730 --> 00:37:31.500
Sufi poet and philosopher
and his brotherhood,

00:37:31.500 --> 00:37:34.620
his following, is properly
called the Mevlevi brotherhood,

00:37:34.620 --> 00:37:39.620
but is popularly known as
the whirling dervishes.

00:37:39.800 --> 00:37:44.170
And so I want to very, very
quickly play 30 seconds

00:37:44.170 --> 00:37:47.409
of this ritual by way of concluding

00:37:47.409 --> 00:37:50.900
and it really doesn't
do justice to the ritual

00:37:50.900 --> 00:37:53.143
which goes on for more than an hour

00:37:53.143 --> 00:37:56.690
but I just want to give
you a sense of how music,

00:37:56.690 --> 00:37:59.780
movement and meditative
focus come together

00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:03.715
in this ritual, do I hit?

00:38:03.715 --> 00:38:06.382
(Arabian music)

00:38:32.980 --> 00:38:35.070
That's very, very short
and doesn't do it justice

00:38:35.070 --> 00:38:37.780
but I hope that conveys
a little bit of how

00:38:37.780 --> 00:38:41.829
through this ritual, this
meditation, Sufis aim

00:38:41.829 --> 00:38:44.823
to transcend time and unify,

00:38:45.719 --> 00:38:47.620
each individual attempts
to unify with the divine

00:38:47.620 --> 00:38:51.480
so in kind of through
these broad brushstrokes

00:38:51.480 --> 00:38:54.960
of time in the Koran, in
the history of science

00:38:54.960 --> 00:38:58.803
and philosophy and
mysticism, I hope that I've

00:38:58.803 --> 00:39:03.180
sort of conveyed that there
is no monolithic concept

00:39:03.180 --> 00:39:06.910
of time in Islam, instead,
it's much more appropriate

00:39:06.910 --> 00:39:10.880
to see time as something
of a canvas where Muslims

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:14.940
sort of contemplated and
explored across the sciences,

00:39:14.940 --> 00:39:17.362
arts and humanities, thank you.

