00:44:31.770 --> 00:44:35.140
of works called At Any Given Moment,

00:44:35.140 --> 00:44:39.040
which they are captured
with a 16 millimeter camera,

00:44:39.040 --> 00:44:42.550
film camera, so that I
can have a materiality

00:44:42.550 --> 00:44:46.010
to the work, they are
captured slightly slower,

00:44:46.010 --> 00:44:47.743
they are 60 frames per second.

00:44:48.800 --> 00:44:52.130
And they are just of these
moments where I found

00:44:52.130 --> 00:44:56.510
one element that was repeated
and repeated and repeated

00:44:56.510 --> 00:44:58.600
but that the light and its modulation

00:44:58.600 --> 00:45:00.972
created incredible complexity.

00:45:00.972 --> 00:45:04.139
(low vibration noise)

00:45:10.150 --> 00:45:12.693
This is called At Any
Given Moment, Fall One.

00:45:13.940 --> 00:45:18.420
And like that I created six in the series.

00:45:18.420 --> 00:45:23.420
They get exhibited at very
large scale, 22 feet by 19,

00:45:24.220 --> 00:45:27.940
with it's very dark but it's
about one ton of lava rock

00:45:27.940 --> 00:45:32.130
and gravel and sand in
front of it, and that again,

00:45:32.130 --> 00:45:36.056
it is I feel that time, I
experience it in my body,

00:45:36.056 --> 00:45:41.056
I need to then create work
that makes me be present

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:44.203
and have a full embodied experience.

00:45:48.380 --> 00:45:53.147
I wrote here, I create
work that makes me feel

00:45:54.040 --> 00:45:59.000
like I am in the very
instant of the present,

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:01.510
it is so easy to be in
the mind, it is so easy

00:46:01.510 --> 00:46:03.733
to be anywhere else, everywhere else.

00:46:05.400 --> 00:46:09.220
And so in this way I also
create a place of repose

00:46:09.220 --> 00:46:13.890
of the soul, 20th century
philosopher Henry Bergson

00:46:13.890 --> 00:46:16.883
has had a profound influence
in my life and work.

00:46:17.820 --> 00:46:20.963
He believed that time was
neither a real phenomenon,

00:46:21.860 --> 00:46:25.930
a real homogenous medium
nor a mental construct

00:46:25.930 --> 00:46:30.460
but possesses what he
referred to as duration.

00:46:30.460 --> 00:46:33.180
Duration in Bergson's view was creativity

00:46:33.180 --> 00:46:37.283
and memory, as an essential
component of reality.

00:46:38.270 --> 00:46:41.850
At the core, a lot of his
ideas were thinking in terms

00:46:41.850 --> 00:46:46.490
of time rather than space,
the very instant of becoming

00:46:46.490 --> 00:46:51.180
is the now, the moment of
action, of the creative act,

00:46:51.180 --> 00:46:55.720
of change, of chance, of
intuition, he said that being

00:46:55.720 --> 00:46:59.000
is in the past and the
present is pure becoming

00:47:00.080 --> 00:47:03.980
so I explored this
through getting a camera

00:47:03.980 --> 00:47:07.830
that was 65 years old, bollocks reflex,

00:47:07.830 --> 00:47:11.290
that I cranked it with
my hand so I could have

00:47:11.290 --> 00:47:15.480
this sense of the apparatus
being an extension of my body

00:47:15.480 --> 00:47:17.830
and therefore I could
not control everything

00:47:17.830 --> 00:47:22.450
and thus the possibility
of chance to happen.

00:47:22.450 --> 00:47:26.120
The possibility of my being
able to through the film

00:47:26.120 --> 00:47:28.910
perhaps stopping and
going, that I could have an

00:47:28.910 --> 00:47:30.653
amorphous sense of the present.

00:47:33.830 --> 00:47:37.380
So in a way, my camera and I

00:47:37.380 --> 00:47:40.613
are becoming with each other, oh boy.

00:47:41.520 --> 00:47:43.690
I told you, time is gonna be an issue.

00:47:43.690 --> 00:47:46.410
It's gonna be an issue, right? (laughs)

00:47:46.410 --> 00:47:48.983
So let me move to the next.

00:47:50.160 --> 00:47:53.200
With this work, I'm then
pushing further this idea

00:47:53.200 --> 00:47:58.100
of using the apparatus
as the 16 millimeter

00:47:58.100 --> 00:48:01.223
because it's a thick material
presence that it has.

00:48:04.290 --> 00:48:08.060
In a way, this work, and I'm
gonna show you this video.

00:48:10.356 --> 00:48:13.356
(atmospheric music)

00:48:14.200 --> 00:48:18.380
By using the 16 millimeter
camera, I tried to have you

00:48:18.380 --> 00:48:20.750
perhaps begin to see
some of the oscillations

00:48:20.750 --> 00:48:25.540
and be aware of its
materiality and so it also

00:48:25.540 --> 00:48:28.570
evokes the idea of looking at looking

00:48:28.570 --> 00:48:32.040
and so you can oscillate
in the present moment,

00:48:32.040 --> 00:48:35.240
you will see that a lot of
my work, I use 16 millimeter,

00:48:35.240 --> 00:48:36.540
and I'll move to the next.

00:48:39.475 --> 00:48:42.320
And I'm literally not even
halfway, so I'm in trouble.

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:47.280
This work, I'm exploring
infinity, the idea that through

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:50.780
the fog, the space that surrounds
me, that sometimes I have

00:48:50.780 --> 00:48:54.940
this line, I can just go
and feel like there is

00:48:54.940 --> 00:48:58.600
something is pulling at
the edges of the universe

00:48:58.600 --> 00:49:01.530
and so for me this is an
exploration through light

00:49:01.530 --> 00:49:06.080
and void of that nothingness
and there's more photographs

00:49:06.080 --> 00:49:09.990
of this and here, I consider
the journey as a medium

00:49:09.990 --> 00:49:12.700
in itself and I have
produced large body of work,

00:49:12.700 --> 00:49:16.923
just looking, going to
extreme and unfamiliar spaces.

00:49:18.470 --> 00:49:21.270
This work is called
walking, I have learned

00:49:21.270 --> 00:49:24.040
that by being in a place,
sometimes waiting 12 hours,

00:49:24.040 --> 00:49:27.190
24 hours, for phenomena
to act differently,

00:49:27.190 --> 00:49:31.400
to perhaps show me a moment of otherness,

00:49:31.400 --> 00:49:35.323
I live in a place where I
can perceive more precisely,

00:49:36.410 --> 00:49:39.970
and this project, I have
myself, I filmed myself

00:49:40.984 --> 00:49:42.280
walking the earth, the
project's called actually

00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:47.280
Walking the Earth, with this work,

00:49:47.320 --> 00:49:51.377
I will end it when I die,
I will go everywhere I go

00:49:51.377 --> 00:49:55.040
and I will film myself
crossing that horizon line.

00:49:55.040 --> 00:49:58.010
I want to see myself,
perhaps, with a little cane

00:49:58.010 --> 00:50:00.788
but just going and
experience my entire life

00:50:00.788 --> 00:50:02.950
walking the horizon.

00:50:02.950 --> 00:50:05.750
French philosopher Michel Surtout argued

00:50:05.750 --> 00:50:07.890
that the practice of walking is analogous

00:50:07.890 --> 00:50:10.870
to the speech act and
can also be understood

00:50:10.870 --> 00:50:15.330
to create a kind of spacing
or syntax in relation to how

00:50:15.330 --> 00:50:19.040
things are encountered, walking
and travel are described

00:50:19.040 --> 00:50:22.840
as a form of enunciation
that carries the possibility

00:50:22.840 --> 00:50:25.920
of breathing life,
introducing a temporal beat

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:26.793
to the narrative.

00:50:32.930 --> 00:50:36.050
So artistic field work is
the closest to what I do

00:50:36.050 --> 00:50:38.600
as an artist in that

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:42.310
I place myself in a situation
where I go into the field,

00:50:42.310 --> 00:50:45.380
I go and experience the
elements, rather than being

00:50:45.380 --> 00:50:48.140
in the studio and trying
to control everything,

00:50:48.140 --> 00:50:51.800
I need to have that relationship
with the environment.

00:50:51.800 --> 00:50:55.910
An artistic field work,
then, is where you have

00:50:55.910 --> 00:50:58.180
the introduction of
different fields of study.

00:50:58.180 --> 00:51:00.540
I could be collaborating with

00:51:00.540 --> 00:51:03.480
a geologist, a glaciologist, scientists

00:51:03.480 --> 00:51:06.350
that are exploring the
earth and then whatever

00:51:06.350 --> 00:51:09.710
you bring back, it can be
in any kind of artifact,

00:51:09.710 --> 00:51:12.199
from a film, a video, a book, a poem.

00:51:12.199 --> 00:51:15.100
And with that I have
created, I have traveled

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:19.540
to Svalbard, to the arctic region,

00:51:19.540 --> 00:51:21.210
following the arctic tern,

00:51:21.210 --> 00:51:24.572
and I'm gonna speak about
this project, Circumsolar,

00:51:24.572 --> 00:51:27.900
which is now becoming with.

00:51:27.900 --> 00:51:31.450
So if we were before
speaking about this becoming

00:51:31.450 --> 00:51:33.750
in the moment of the present of Bergson,

00:51:33.750 --> 00:51:36.370
this idea of becoming with so a little bit

00:51:36.370 --> 00:51:41.370
of Donna Harroway's idea
of the world in together

00:51:41.450 --> 00:51:44.383
with other species, with Circumsolar,

00:51:46.818 --> 00:51:49.520
it's a longterm project
with a growing body

00:51:49.520 --> 00:51:52.240
of artworks that emerge
from my profound love

00:51:52.240 --> 00:51:55.738
of the arctic tern, its
unwavering determination

00:51:55.738 --> 00:51:58.535
and the space it occupies in our earth

00:51:58.535 --> 00:52:01.293
and our imagination.

00:52:02.981 --> 00:52:06.360
Every year, the arctic
tern, a small seabird,

00:52:06.360 --> 00:52:10.120
flies from the arctic to the
antarctic and back again,

00:52:10.120 --> 00:52:13.930
making its migratory journey
the longest every recorded.

00:52:13.930 --> 00:52:16.180
As a result, the arctic
tern experiences two

00:52:16.180 --> 00:52:19.610
polar summers in a year, which
makes it the only creature

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:22.080
that lives the most daylight,
and that's a little bit,

00:52:22.080 --> 00:52:24.670
you get a sense of its trajectory,

00:52:24.670 --> 00:52:26.070
so this is a project that I,

00:52:26.070 --> 00:52:28.670
it's a project that again, it might be one

00:52:28.670 --> 00:52:30.940
that I will have my entire
life that I'll be doing

00:52:30.940 --> 00:52:35.480
this project, this is, I
created a video that focuses on

00:52:35.480 --> 00:52:40.480
the arctic tern's mating
and breeding season,

00:52:42.420 --> 00:52:45.680
but the arctic tern is a
canary in the coal mine.

00:52:45.680 --> 00:52:46.853
It is basically,

00:52:48.290 --> 00:52:51.240
in 2012 we collaborated
with an ornithologist

00:52:51.240 --> 00:52:53.780
and 90% of the chicks are
dying because of the way

00:52:53.780 --> 00:52:57.023
in which the water is
warming up all around it.

00:52:59.070 --> 00:53:02.650
And it was exhibited at
Globe that Mark Pally is here

00:53:02.650 --> 00:53:06.353
and he was the creative
artistic director of the show.

00:53:08.040 --> 00:53:11.640
And you can see it in my website,

00:53:11.640 --> 00:53:14.053
it's called circumsolar migration one.

00:53:14.911 --> 00:53:16.010
(atmospheric music)

00:53:16.010 --> 00:53:19.920
And it focuses on the migration of humans,

00:53:19.920 --> 00:53:21.910
of all creatures and that we must be

00:53:21.910 --> 00:53:24.275
in movement and in time.

