00:55:08.500 --> 00:55:10.180
My approach to time

00:55:11.830 --> 00:55:16.420
as everyone else's is,
is extremely personal

00:55:16.420 --> 00:55:18.280
and to really

00:55:19.926 --> 00:55:23.180
give an eye into my
research, I have to give you

00:55:23.180 --> 00:55:28.180
a little bit of my past and
how my life has impacted

00:55:28.320 --> 00:55:32.020
the way that I look at
time so I'd like to start

00:55:32.020 --> 00:55:35.260
by just talking about a few things.

00:55:35.260 --> 00:55:39.340
Musical time changes
from culture to culture.

00:55:39.340 --> 00:55:43.840
Seconds pass by in the same
manner throughout the world,

00:55:43.840 --> 00:55:48.840
however, musical time is
reflective of cultural influences

00:55:49.868 --> 00:55:53.170
and expressions, so one
of the things I wanted

00:55:53.170 --> 00:55:56.850
to talk about first is
a couple of concerts

00:55:56.850 --> 00:56:00.740
that occurred in New York
city about a month apart

00:56:00.740 --> 00:56:05.740
when I was 29 years old, the
first was at Carnegie Hall

00:56:06.240 --> 00:56:08.723
and it was with Winton
Marcellus, Bobby McPheron,

00:56:11.330 --> 00:56:14.890
Anthony Davis, a professor at UCSD now,

00:56:14.890 --> 00:56:18.490
a dear colleague of mine,
and a number of young

00:56:18.490 --> 00:56:22.393
musical masters, it was called
the young lions concert.

00:56:23.840 --> 00:56:28.523
And the music that was
played was modern jazz.

00:56:29.520 --> 00:56:33.320
And so one of the points is that

00:56:33.320 --> 00:56:38.320
the approach to time,
metrical time, a steady pulse,

00:56:38.320 --> 00:56:43.320
was hyper precise and the
way that time was approached,

00:56:45.470 --> 00:56:50.470
you could spread your emotions
over that hyper precision,

00:56:50.640 --> 00:56:54.150
but one of the things that
had to occur is the fact

00:56:54.150 --> 00:56:59.150
that everybody had to
agree where the time was.

00:57:00.680 --> 00:57:04.310
You have to find that
commonality, you have to come

00:57:04.310 --> 00:57:08.130
together, and you're taking
in not only what people

00:57:08.130 --> 00:57:12.163
are playing technically,
but you're also intaking

00:57:12.163 --> 00:57:16.313
what they are playing emotionally.

00:57:18.260 --> 00:57:22.810
Okay, the second concert,
I was one of three soloists

00:57:22.810 --> 00:57:27.393
at Lincoln Center with
the New York Philharmonic.

00:57:28.700 --> 00:57:30.653
Walked out on the stage.

00:57:32.040 --> 00:57:37.040
And amazing experience
and this concert was,

00:57:37.240 --> 00:57:38.853
yeah, I said Lincoln Center.

00:57:40.500 --> 00:57:44.810
The conductor gave his
downbeat and the orchestra

00:57:44.810 --> 00:57:48.373
came in slightly behind the beat.

00:57:49.420 --> 00:57:51.475
I said, oh, God.

00:57:51.475 --> 00:57:54.308
(audience laughs)

00:57:56.266 --> 00:57:59.473
Thank God I didn't have
to play that first chord,

00:58:00.620 --> 00:58:03.990
but one thing that I knew

00:58:03.990 --> 00:58:07.410
because classical music,

00:58:07.410 --> 00:58:10.920
a lot of it the time, the way it unfolds,

00:58:10.920 --> 00:58:15.000
the tempo, the pace of it is flexible

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:18.730
to fit the particular emotions that exist

00:58:18.730 --> 00:58:23.510
within the composition so I had to play

00:58:23.510 --> 00:58:28.510
in a very different way, I
also had to perceive time

00:58:28.830 --> 00:58:32.260
in a different way than
the experience with

00:58:32.260 --> 00:58:34.610
Winton Marcellus and Bobby McPheron.

00:58:34.610 --> 00:58:37.560
And so on, so musicians, what do we do?

00:58:37.560 --> 00:58:39.430
Composers, what do we do?

00:58:39.430 --> 00:58:43.630
We learn different cultural approaches

00:58:43.630 --> 00:58:47.270
and we bring them into
what it is that we do

00:58:48.350 --> 00:58:50.993
and I think one other very quick point,

00:58:52.050 --> 00:58:54.483
time is like a mystic.

00:58:57.200 --> 00:58:58.193
You're chasing it.

00:59:00.080 --> 00:59:01.693
You want to learn more.

00:59:03.230 --> 00:59:06.020
You want to understand,

00:59:06.020 --> 00:59:08.500
you want to become more intimate with time

00:59:08.500 --> 00:59:11.421
because the more intimate with time,

00:59:11.421 --> 00:59:16.421
the more profundity that can
exist in your compositions

00:59:17.390 --> 00:59:22.390
and also your improvisations,
so with that being said,

00:59:24.040 --> 00:59:25.330
what I would like to do

00:59:26.860 --> 00:59:29.483
is could you play this video please?

00:59:31.920 --> 00:59:34.670
We'll hear a few minutes of
it, I should let you know

00:59:34.670 --> 00:59:39.670
this is an incredible Senegalese composer,

00:59:39.810 --> 00:59:44.810
Doudou N'diyae Rose and
this is his ensemble

00:59:45.950 --> 00:59:48.560
and one of the things that happens,

00:59:48.560 --> 00:59:51.305
can you turn it up a little
bit, you got to feel it,

00:59:51.305 --> 00:59:54.803
there you go, he's calling the ensemble,

00:59:56.259 --> 00:59:59.842
they're getting up,
he's letting them know,

01:00:01.110 --> 01:00:03.717
he doesn't say, okay, the
rehearsal's gonna begin,

01:00:03.717 --> 01:00:07.580
he calls them with the sabar, on the side,

01:00:07.580 --> 01:00:11.290
that's what we call a
toe post, that's a short

01:00:11.290 --> 01:00:15.559
rhythmical phrase and all of
the music is built around that.

01:00:15.559 --> 01:00:17.976
(drum music)

01:01:14.185 --> 01:01:16.669
The tempo's gonna get a
little faster, just slightly.

01:01:16.669 --> 01:01:19.086
(drum music)

01:01:48.810 --> 01:01:50.928
I hated to stop it, oh.

01:01:50.928 --> 01:01:51.761
(audience laughs)

01:01:51.761 --> 01:01:56.670
But you can find it's online,
it's Doudou, D-O-U-D-O-U,

01:01:56.670 --> 01:02:01.070
N, apostrophe, D-I-Y-A-E Rose,

01:02:03.889 --> 01:02:04.722
and it's called the rose rhythm.

01:02:04.722 --> 01:02:06.580
Did you hear a lot of
rhythms stacked on top

01:02:06.580 --> 01:02:08.210
of one another?

01:02:08.210 --> 01:02:12.640
We call those polyrhythms,
guess what's really important.

01:02:12.640 --> 01:02:15.453
The rhythms speak to one another,

01:02:16.740 --> 01:02:19.410
this communication is so essential,

01:02:19.410 --> 01:02:22.690
it's such a key part of African music

01:02:22.690 --> 01:02:25.830
where you have multiple
rhythms that are speaking

01:02:25.830 --> 01:02:28.580
to one another and they're all stacked up

01:02:28.580 --> 01:02:32.453
and they're in communion with one another.

01:02:34.524 --> 01:02:38.600
So let's look at this, when
I think about time in music,

01:02:38.600 --> 01:02:41.100
I think about it primarily in three ways,

01:02:41.100 --> 01:02:42.943
on the level of the individual,

01:02:43.990 --> 01:02:48.580
you can get a wide range of
the most profound aspects

01:02:48.580 --> 01:02:52.700
of the human condition
communicated by the way

01:02:52.700 --> 01:02:54.970
