01:21:07.790 --> 01:21:11.770
our writing and our research,
our scholarly production

01:21:11.770 --> 01:21:14.880
as something that will
enable us to connect

01:21:14.880 --> 01:21:17.390
with an eternal, right,
your writings outlive you,

01:21:17.390 --> 01:21:20.480
your works and that, your
compositions outlive you,

01:21:20.480 --> 01:21:24.490
right, but I have to say
that that is something

01:21:24.490 --> 01:21:28.060
that I only think about
when really pushed to it.

01:21:28.060 --> 01:21:30.170
I mean, the moments in
which I actually think

01:21:30.170 --> 01:21:33.550
about eternity is when I think
about Islamic philosophy,

01:21:33.550 --> 01:21:37.500
for example, I mean, it really
is a very abstract notion

01:21:37.500 --> 01:21:40.130
for me and that's why it
was interesting for me

01:21:40.130 --> 01:21:45.130
to think about the Muslim
mystics and the ways in which

01:21:47.240 --> 01:21:50.350
through a particular ritual,
I mean, there is this idea

01:21:50.350 --> 01:21:52.510
that you can actually experience eternity,

01:21:52.510 --> 01:21:54.373
I mean, you can experience time,

01:21:55.561 --> 01:21:57.270
you can experience the
past through the present,

01:21:57.270 --> 01:22:02.220
and a future moment of happiness

01:22:02.220 --> 01:22:06.150
through this, through an
embodiment, through a ritual

01:22:06.150 --> 01:22:09.740
so I found that interesting
but beyond that I have to say

01:22:09.740 --> 01:22:12.740
university time, I am
very much in the moment,

01:22:12.740 --> 01:22:15.541
what do I have to do next, right,

01:22:15.541 --> 01:22:17.260
there's a time panel I have to go to

01:22:17.260 --> 01:22:20.430
and then there's a reception,
so I think that's how

01:22:20.430 --> 01:22:23.713
most of our days are lived. (laughs)

01:22:24.610 --> 01:22:28.140
- I think that in a few projects, I have

01:22:29.520 --> 01:22:34.151
looked for that specific idea of infinity,

01:22:34.151 --> 01:22:37.560
like you see those photographs
and then the nothing further

01:22:37.560 --> 01:22:42.010
happens video in which I am
really kind of meditating

01:22:42.010 --> 01:22:46.740
on the idea of the sublime but
in terms of the disappearance

01:22:46.740 --> 01:22:50.820
of oneself or that connection
of oneself with the earth

01:22:50.820 --> 01:22:53.270
so it's truly the dissolution of

01:22:53.270 --> 01:22:56.830
a sense of individuality
and becoming matter

01:22:56.830 --> 01:23:01.385
and becoming more universal and I think

01:23:01.385 --> 01:23:05.410
of, you know, when I
think of the universe,

01:23:05.410 --> 01:23:06.657
when I think of (speaks foreign language),

01:23:07.570 --> 01:23:11.627
this incredible understanding
that we have of everything,

01:23:11.627 --> 01:23:14.210
there's the corners of
it, it's when I think

01:23:14.210 --> 01:23:17.530
of that infinity but
it does not include me

01:23:17.530 --> 01:23:21.010
as a human as much, right,
it includes it as thought

01:23:21.010 --> 01:23:24.010
because immediately I
come back like a yoyo

01:23:24.010 --> 01:23:26.730
and come back to extinction
and what we're doing

01:23:26.730 --> 01:23:31.730
with the planet and that I
don't see us as living beings,

01:23:31.785 --> 01:23:34.963
with that sense of, you know,

01:23:36.440 --> 01:23:38.520
unlimited existence.

01:23:38.520 --> 01:23:41.900
On the other hand, it
really puts me exactly at,

01:23:41.900 --> 01:23:45.820
what was it that the
humans existed only in

01:23:45.820 --> 01:23:49.070
what's the equivalent
of the last millimeter

01:23:49.070 --> 01:23:52.970
of the last square of a toilet paper roll?

01:23:52.970 --> 01:23:56.370
Right, we consider the
existence of the universe,

01:23:56.370 --> 01:23:59.670
that little little little thing is us.

01:23:59.670 --> 01:24:04.170
So when I think infinity,
I think more geologically

01:24:04.170 --> 01:24:07.980
and universal, not necessarily
as existence as humans,

01:24:07.980 --> 01:24:11.563
and so therefore I do feel
immediately, boom, our finality.

01:24:15.010 --> 01:24:16.930
- First of all, even before I comment,

01:24:16.930 --> 01:24:21.150
I want to say how moved
I was by your images.

01:24:21.150 --> 01:24:24.810
The images of infinity
were just so touching,

01:24:24.810 --> 01:24:28.073
I just want to stand over
here and start crying.

01:24:28.073 --> 01:24:30.030
(audience laughs)

01:24:30.030 --> 01:24:34.403
And from everyone, it's
just been a really beautiful

01:24:34.403 --> 01:24:36.383
profound experience.

01:24:37.450 --> 01:24:41.200
I have to say I'm thinking
about eternity daily

01:24:42.319 --> 01:24:44.550
and the reason

01:24:47.010 --> 01:24:48.173
is twofold.

01:24:50.470 --> 01:24:51.883
My faith is my life.

01:24:53.260 --> 01:24:54.093
And

01:24:55.120 --> 01:24:58.940
it impacts everything that I try to do.

01:24:58.940 --> 01:25:00.800
When I come to this institution

01:25:01.643 --> 01:25:06.643
to give the best of what I
have, my faith informs me.

01:25:07.750 --> 01:25:10.443
When I go home and I
have the time to compose,

01:25:12.100 --> 01:25:13.513
it's an offering to God.

01:25:14.720 --> 01:25:19.593
And I feel that when I'm
in that room, I'm visited.

01:25:23.830 --> 01:25:24.663
And

01:25:25.840 --> 01:25:29.893
it, the visitation informs the music.

01:25:31.310 --> 01:25:33.240
The visitation guides the music,

01:25:33.240 --> 01:25:34.573
it leads the music.

01:25:36.360 --> 01:25:38.640
And I set texts from the Old Testament,

01:25:38.640 --> 01:25:40.950
the New Testament, I've

01:25:42.490 --> 01:25:45.640
sort of turned my back
on the commercial world

01:25:45.640 --> 01:25:50.413
years ago, and this is the
only thing I want to do.

01:25:51.650 --> 01:25:55.080
And I just came back from a
conference at the Vatican.

01:25:55.080 --> 01:26:00.080
I was invited by the head
of culture for the Vatican

01:26:01.810 --> 01:26:05.590
and the conference was amazing,
people from 36 countries

01:26:05.590 --> 01:26:09.490
coming together to talk about music,

01:26:09.490 --> 01:26:10.323
and God.

01:26:10.323 --> 01:26:13.070
Words and God.

01:26:13.070 --> 01:26:17.610
And you come back from
that experience and being

01:26:17.610 --> 01:26:21.263
at Assisi, you know, where
Saint Francis is buried,

01:26:25.440 --> 01:26:27.513
and I think about Mahalia Jackson,

01:26:28.780 --> 01:26:33.606
the great gospel singer
who could have sang

01:26:33.606 --> 01:26:37.940
any music that she wanted
to, including opera

01:26:37.940 --> 01:26:41.140
and so many other forms,
but everything she did

01:26:41.140 --> 01:26:45.050
was an offering to God, so
I figured I was so crazy

01:26:45.050 --> 01:26:48.080
and so bad when I was young,
I've got to do better now.

01:26:48.080 --> 01:26:50.913
(audience laughs)

01:26:52.710 --> 01:26:55.397
- Wonderful, I think it's
time for us to open up

01:26:55.397 --> 01:26:56.560
the conversation to everybody in the room,

01:26:56.560 --> 01:26:57.393
if we can do that.

01:26:57.393 --> 01:26:59.933
We've got a couple of
microphones in the room.

01:27:04.600 --> 01:27:07.493
I see a question right
up here up front, yep,

01:27:08.430 --> 01:27:10.353
if we can get a microphone over here.

01:27:18.380 --> 01:27:20.960
- Oh, okay, hello, so I think you guys

01:27:20.960 --> 01:27:24.600
all gave like a very marvelous,
like, summary of your own

01:27:24.600 --> 01:27:27.724
idea of time which I was
really moved by each and every

01:27:27.724 --> 01:27:30.376
single one of them, but I was wondering,

01:27:30.376 --> 01:27:31.720
time is such a vast topic,
like, anyone could agree

01:27:31.720 --> 01:27:33.380
that time is vast and they usually take,

01:27:33.380 --> 01:27:35.724
like if you ask someone with
all of these 10 questions

01:27:35.724 --> 01:27:37.130
that you ask, like what
is time, what is beauty,

01:27:37.130 --> 01:27:39.480
what is space and everyone
kind of pauses for a second

01:27:39.480 --> 01:27:41.710
and they don't know quite how to answer,

01:27:41.710 --> 01:27:43.160
would you agree that
one of the reasons why

01:27:43.160 --> 01:27:47.010
it's very difficult to, I
don't know, express or define

01:27:47.010 --> 01:27:50.630
or give a very like clear
answer to what is time

01:27:50.630 --> 01:27:53.440
is because we as humans
don't have enough time

01:27:53.440 --> 01:27:57.390
to even begin to like start explaining

01:27:57.390 --> 01:28:00.326
what we're trying to say
and how was it that you guys

01:28:00.326 --> 01:28:03.201
managed to summarize all of these things,

01:28:03.201 --> 01:28:04.170
because I noticed some
of you were like trying

01:28:04.170 --> 01:28:05.650
to rush through and I could
tell you didn't want to

01:28:05.650 --> 01:28:07.730
but how did you manage
to crunch it all into

01:28:07.730 --> 01:28:09.943
like a small space of speaking time?

01:28:12.310 --> 01:28:13.994
- Obviously, I failed.

01:28:13.994 --> 01:28:16.340
(audience laughs)

01:28:16.340 --> 01:28:18.083
It seems that mine went on and on.

01:28:21.810 --> 01:28:22.643
Well.

01:28:24.630 --> 01:28:28.520
I think that it's just
the moment that you know

01:28:28.520 --> 01:28:33.110
that you're basically having
a glimpse at something,

01:28:33.110 --> 01:28:36.253
I mean, really, even what we said,

01:28:37.230 --> 01:28:39.110
it's a glimpse of

01:28:40.710 --> 01:28:42.770
what someone can be doing
the rest of their life.

01:28:42.770 --> 01:28:47.110
I mean, I think that for some
of us, our thinking of time

01:28:47.110 --> 01:28:51.790
has really been all our lives
and so now it's more like

01:28:51.790 --> 01:28:55.320
okay, let's kind of, like
a lick of a cat, like,

01:28:55.320 --> 01:28:58.347
that's what you got because
that's very, very little,

01:28:58.347 --> 01:29:01.570
but it's...

01:29:01.570 --> 01:29:03.940
For me, it's like being
in, trying to figure out

01:29:03.940 --> 01:29:06.123
what does it mean to me in this instant.

01:29:09.110 --> 01:29:11.010
- Anyone else about the
panel on this question

01:29:11.010 --> 01:29:12.660
about how did you do it,
how did you get it down

01:29:12.660 --> 01:29:14.023
to 10 minutes?

01:29:14.900 --> 01:29:16.850
- Well, look, I mean,
I don't have an answer

01:29:16.850 --> 01:29:18.660
for how did I get it down to 10 minutes,

01:29:18.660 --> 01:29:21.767
but just to continue on
something that we touched on

01:29:21.767 --> 01:29:25.150
before, I have to confess
that when I first received

01:29:25.150 --> 01:29:30.150
this invitation, the only
thing that came to my mind were

01:29:31.410 --> 01:29:34.490
jokes about Pakistani standard
time and Middle Eastern

01:29:34.490 --> 01:29:35.780
standard time.
(audience laughs)

01:29:35.780 --> 01:29:39.116
That's like what you use when
you're always late, right?

01:29:39.116 --> 01:29:41.199
- That is so funny.
- But.

01:29:42.396 --> 01:29:45.600
I know, I thought what am
I gonna say for 10 minutes?

01:29:45.600 --> 01:29:49.890
But it really was an
opportunity for me to explore

01:29:49.890 --> 01:29:52.850
all of these
interdisciplinary connections,

01:29:52.850 --> 01:29:55.840
some of which I was unaware
of, I was mostly aware

01:29:55.840 --> 01:30:00.040
of time and Islamic
philosophy, but I thought

01:30:00.040 --> 01:30:02.527
one of the things that I
want to do in this panel

01:30:02.527 --> 01:30:07.527
is to show the interdisciplinary
nature of engagement

01:30:07.940 --> 01:30:10.870
with time across a religious civilization

01:30:10.870 --> 01:30:13.710
and I thought, what are some of the things

01:30:13.710 --> 01:30:18.710
that I can pick that would
be appropriate for this type

01:30:18.790 --> 01:30:20.710
of a setting and how
can I just get it down

01:30:20.710 --> 01:30:24.006
to two minutes per thing, so yeah.

01:30:24.006 --> 01:30:25.820
- [Moderator] Wonderful.

01:30:25.820 --> 01:30:29.140
- I chose the three musical
examples sort of first

01:30:29.140 --> 01:30:30.740
and then started thinking about it more,

01:30:30.740 --> 01:30:33.170
did any of you have a chance
to listen to the musical

01:30:33.170 --> 01:30:35.713
examples, a few of you did, great.

01:30:38.112 --> 01:30:41.463
I also wanted to include
Japanese gagaku music

01:30:42.819 --> 01:30:47.819
because there is a sense
of floating at times

01:30:48.450 --> 01:30:51.080
about how the music unfolds.

01:30:51.080 --> 01:30:56.080
And the deep meditation that
the music is based on in part

01:30:58.480 --> 01:31:01.740
and just the profundity of the sound

01:31:01.740 --> 01:31:05.091
and at times it's almost
like the sound is swirling

01:31:05.091 --> 01:31:09.135
in the room and if you
get that kind of feeling,

01:31:09.135 --> 01:31:13.057
you're going to go
somewhere else very quickly.

01:31:13.057 --> 01:31:14.602
(audience laughs)

01:31:14.602 --> 01:31:17.190
You know, and how that
happens all over the world

01:31:17.190 --> 01:31:21.340
has really fascinated me
so then after thinking

01:31:21.340 --> 01:31:26.340
of the three musical examples,
it was more trying to not

01:31:27.600 --> 01:31:28.933
spread too wide.

01:31:30.400 --> 01:31:34.667
And just try to keep it fairly
focused and I also failed.

01:31:34.667 --> 01:31:36.701
(audience laughs)

01:31:36.701 --> 01:31:38.730
- No you didn't.
- Not at all.

01:31:38.730 --> 01:31:40.343
- It's hard, it's really hard.

01:31:41.780 --> 01:31:42.613
- Yes please.

01:31:44.470 --> 01:31:48.720
- Again, I really enjoyed
the talk and it reminded me

01:31:48.720 --> 01:31:50.810
a lot about some of the
elements that came up

01:31:50.810 --> 01:31:55.450
in last week's with
space and my question is

01:31:55.450 --> 01:31:59.000
do you see time, especially
since your disciplines,

01:31:59.000 --> 01:32:01.620
time in some ways, is
it the canvas on which

01:32:01.620 --> 01:32:04.770
you do your work as a
musician, as a photographer,

01:32:04.770 --> 01:32:08.910
as a filmmaker, as a
historian, or is time itself

01:32:10.110 --> 01:32:14.900
a tangible thing or is it
just a relationship of ideas

01:32:14.900 --> 01:32:18.630
and do you see it as
a very objective thing

01:32:18.630 --> 01:32:21.300
or a subjective thing, where does it lie?

01:32:21.300 --> 01:32:23.380
And also I just wanted to
chide you for not having

01:32:23.380 --> 01:32:25.688
your astrophysicist here
because if you're going talk

01:32:25.688 --> 01:32:29.500
about time, so just, that relationship,

01:32:29.500 --> 01:32:33.713
do you see time as some
actual tangible thing?

01:32:36.320 --> 01:32:38.910
- Yes.
- Yeah, sure.

01:32:38.910 --> 01:32:42.773
- There's a great blues
line by Robert Johnson.

01:32:43.750 --> 01:32:47.740
And it starts, I woke up this morning

01:32:47.740 --> 01:32:50.690
and I saw the blues
walking down the street

01:32:50.690 --> 01:32:54.393
just like a man, what a
blues, gimme your right hand.

01:32:55.890 --> 01:33:00.487
So the rhythm of the lyric, you know,

01:33:00.487 --> 01:33:03.280
he's giving you a tangible
image, he's taking the blues

01:33:03.280 --> 01:33:08.280
and he's turning it into a
person and all of that happens

01:33:08.310 --> 01:33:13.120
while he is singing with one
rhythm, playing rhythm guitar,

01:33:13.120 --> 01:33:15.900
with another rhythm
and playing lead guitar

01:33:15.900 --> 01:33:20.900
with another rhythm, so just think about

01:33:20.930 --> 01:33:22.363
what you'd have to do.

01:33:24.360 --> 01:33:28.393
To have your brain do all
of that at the same time.

01:33:31.596 --> 01:33:32.942
You know?

01:33:32.942 --> 01:33:35.670
And so it's tangible and it's also

01:33:38.380 --> 01:33:40.193
abstract, both.

01:33:42.150 --> 01:33:45.290
- Wonderful, let's carry on
with the, yes, right here.

01:33:45.290 --> 01:33:46.880
Sorry, don't mean to be
in one area of the room,

01:33:46.880 --> 01:33:49.820
we're gonna spread it
out a little bit, but.

01:33:49.820 --> 01:33:52.150
- Hi, thank you all for speaking.

01:33:52.150 --> 01:33:55.370
My question is directed
mostly to the two artists

01:33:55.370 --> 01:33:58.050
on the panel and I was
just curious, the thing

01:33:58.050 --> 01:34:00.930
that struck the most
about what everyone said

01:34:00.930 --> 01:34:03.620
but specifically the two of you was time

01:34:03.620 --> 01:34:06.183
or art as a way of
stepping outside of time

01:34:06.183 --> 01:34:09.400
and the sort of constraining
element that our modern

01:34:09.400 --> 01:34:11.870
conception of that has on our daily lives

01:34:11.870 --> 01:34:14.590
and I was curious, though, that even,

01:34:14.590 --> 01:34:17.030
we see art as a sort of
profession that exists

01:34:17.030 --> 01:34:19.160
outside of that, but it does still exist

01:34:19.160 --> 01:34:21.390
in a capitalistic art market,

01:34:21.390 --> 01:34:23.856
that has a demand for
labor and trade and time

01:34:23.856 --> 01:34:27.750
and so I'm curious about how you at, like,

01:34:27.750 --> 01:34:30.830
in your practices, how
you guys deal with that,

01:34:30.830 --> 01:34:33.283
if you have any strategies or advice?

01:34:34.950 --> 01:34:38.330
- I mean, it's an interesting
thing in terms of,

01:34:38.330 --> 01:34:40.980
it's almost like I want
to answer a combination

01:34:40.980 --> 01:34:45.980
of how do I experience
time because so many times

01:34:46.870 --> 01:34:48.590
in my life somebody has come and said,

01:34:48.590 --> 01:34:51.823
well, what you do is
like, it's not real life,

01:34:52.710 --> 01:34:54.920
it's just, and all I can think is well,

01:34:54.920 --> 01:34:57.270
you make the life you want.

01:34:57.270 --> 01:35:01.010
And so in terms of the

01:35:01.930 --> 01:35:04.442
living or being, you know,

01:35:04.442 --> 01:35:09.150
is time a real thing, is like
as I mentioned in my talk,

01:35:09.150 --> 01:35:13.557
it's like I am time, so
it's as real as I can be

01:35:13.557 --> 01:35:16.350
and I can be real sometimes
and I can be very unreal

01:35:16.350 --> 01:35:20.440
at other times so it's so much about

01:35:20.440 --> 01:35:21.310
where

01:35:22.530 --> 01:35:25.150
what you want to do with your life,

01:35:25.150 --> 01:35:27.880
how do you schedule it,
then you cannot say,

01:35:27.880 --> 01:35:30.190
when I have time, I'm going to do art

01:35:30.190 --> 01:35:32.300
or when I have time, no.

01:35:32.300 --> 01:35:34.740
It is what it is, it's
like I cannot help it,

01:35:34.740 --> 01:35:37.887
I have to be making it, otherwise it is

01:35:37.887 --> 01:35:42.010
like there is no air inside
of me so you have to live it,

01:35:42.010 --> 01:35:44.880
breathe it, on the other
hand, is there a time

01:35:44.880 --> 01:35:48.570
where I can actually step
out and stick to a timeline

01:35:48.570 --> 01:35:51.890
like for a talk, right, so
for me, I have the other

01:35:53.210 --> 01:35:58.210
problem, is that can I actually
step to do certain things

01:36:00.140 --> 01:36:03.283
that are very pragmatic and
that I really would be measured,

01:36:03.283 --> 01:36:06.623
it's like no, it's all
fluidity and sometimes

01:36:06.623 --> 01:36:10.090
even in paying a bill right
here and I'm making art

01:36:10.090 --> 01:36:13.990
right here, and it's just,
I'm more like this thing

01:36:13.990 --> 01:36:16.514
and (makes silly noises).

01:36:16.514 --> 01:36:18.540
(audience laughs)

01:36:18.540 --> 01:36:19.977
- I love it.

01:36:19.977 --> 01:36:23.790
- That is, there isn't such a
thing as compartmentalization

01:36:23.790 --> 01:36:26.643
when you are an artist, I think, yeah.

01:36:28.176 --> 01:36:31.176
(audience applauds)

01:36:33.050 --> 01:36:35.953
- It's about your self
discovery as an artist.

01:36:37.450 --> 01:36:39.870
And really finding out who you are

01:36:40.710 --> 01:36:45.410
and what you have to say
that differentiates you

01:36:45.410 --> 01:36:48.630
from every other artist on
the planet and trying to be

01:36:48.630 --> 01:36:52.620
as great as you possibly
can, so many people think

01:36:52.620 --> 01:36:55.970
about the business of art and visual art.

01:36:55.970 --> 01:36:59.680
It's such a big deal now with the people

01:36:59.680 --> 01:37:01.740
that have made a lot of
money from the stock market

01:37:01.740 --> 01:37:04.240
going and investing in art that becomes

01:37:05.230 --> 01:37:06.910
very fashionable.

01:37:06.910 --> 01:37:09.540
Then they run on to someone
else and someone else

01:37:09.540 --> 01:37:11.943
so if you aim for the timeless,

01:37:13.491 --> 01:37:14.683
you are free.

01:37:15.565 --> 01:37:17.100
(audience applauds)

01:37:17.100 --> 01:37:19.487
- That's beautiful, yes, yes, yes.

01:37:20.470 --> 01:37:23.853
- Wonderful, over on this
side, I see a hand, yep.

01:37:28.460 --> 01:37:30.380
- I'd like to say thank you all again

01:37:30.380 --> 01:37:35.170
and to you, what role
does timelessness play

01:37:35.170 --> 01:37:37.053
in the scheme of time?

01:37:41.120 --> 01:37:43.640
- I'm sorry, was that?

01:37:43.640 --> 01:37:46.470
- I think that's open
to anyone on the panel.

01:37:46.470 --> 01:37:51.050
What role does timelessness
play in your own lives

01:37:51.050 --> 01:37:51.933
or your own work?

01:37:57.600 --> 01:37:59.650
- I mean, you just said it, it's freedom.

01:38:00.690 --> 01:38:01.523
- It is freedom.

01:38:01.523 --> 01:38:04.070
- That, I mean, it's...

01:38:09.790 --> 01:38:14.080
- I mean, one thing that I
realized from this panel is

01:38:15.320 --> 01:38:19.313
that musicians, artists,

01:38:22.355 --> 01:38:24.240
people who live in the
creating realm in ways

01:38:24.240 --> 01:38:27.410
different from what I do is

01:38:28.940 --> 01:38:32.070
are those who really
experience time and probably

01:38:32.070 --> 01:38:35.590
timelessness far more
fully that I have ever

01:38:35.590 --> 01:38:38.740
had the blessing to do so because for me,

01:38:38.740 --> 01:38:41.200
time is essentially, it's a clock,

01:38:41.200 --> 01:38:45.950
it's something that ultimately
can be very oppressive

01:38:45.950 --> 01:38:50.740
and so to think about
experiencing timelessness

01:38:50.740 --> 01:38:53.440
as I think you both have is not something

01:38:53.440 --> 01:38:57.928
that I have given much time
to, I have to say. (laughs)

01:38:57.928 --> 01:38:59.200
- Well, probably,

01:38:59.200 --> 01:39:01.470
I think that's probably not entirely true

01:39:01.470 --> 01:39:03.580
because I think that one of the things is

01:39:03.580 --> 01:39:06.150
time becomes oppressive in our society,

01:39:06.150 --> 01:39:09.422
I mean, it goes back to the question of

01:39:09.422 --> 01:39:14.010
the young woman asked,
it is constantly present,

01:39:14.010 --> 01:39:16.500
you are constantly reminded of
it whether you like it or not

01:39:16.500 --> 01:39:18.780
and you're constantly trying
to configure your life

01:39:18.780 --> 01:39:21.706
against it or whatever it
is because of deadlines

01:39:21.706 --> 01:39:24.270
or because of needs and so the project

01:39:24.270 --> 01:39:26.967
of stepping out of time
becomes I think priceless

01:39:26.967 --> 01:39:29.970
and I think that can happen
in many different ways.

01:39:29.970 --> 01:39:32.920
It's living in the moment,
where there is no time,

01:39:32.920 --> 01:39:37.920
where time is eternal, which
are perhaps synonymous,

01:39:38.530 --> 01:39:41.670
or living in a state of
rhythm where you lose a sense

01:39:41.670 --> 01:39:46.484
of not the, you're so immediate in timing

01:39:46.484 --> 01:39:49.520
that you lose a sense
of the larger context

01:39:49.520 --> 01:39:51.920
so I think that notion,
I think we all aspire

01:39:51.920 --> 01:39:54.970
to stepping out of time,
of not being oppressed

01:39:54.970 --> 01:39:56.543
and finding ways in which we can do that.

01:39:56.543 --> 01:40:00.010
You can do it in reading,
you know, when you're really

01:40:00.010 --> 01:40:03.583
studying about something,
you can lose where you are.

01:40:03.583 --> 01:40:06.730
I mean, I can go into an
archive and spend a day there

01:40:06.730 --> 01:40:10.663
and forget how, it's not dictated
by the hours I was there,

01:40:10.663 --> 01:40:13.790
it's dictated by the project,
and it's that project

01:40:13.790 --> 01:40:17.530
which is, I mean, it's boring
and tedious for everybody else

01:40:17.530 --> 01:40:21.200
but for me it was fantastic, and

01:40:21.200 --> 01:40:23.600
so I think that that's, I think we all,

01:40:23.600 --> 01:40:26.070
and I think that's the modern
dilemma in a lot of ways

01:40:26.070 --> 01:40:29.010
is trying to find that
way in which you're not

01:40:29.010 --> 01:40:31.860
oppressed by time which time
is not dictating everything

01:40:31.860 --> 01:40:35.553
you're doing and the more you can do that,

01:40:35.553 --> 01:40:39.240
I think the better off
you are but it's singular.

01:40:39.240 --> 01:40:43.100
It can be through music,
it can be through art,

01:40:43.100 --> 01:40:46.440
it can be through
scholarship, it can be through

01:40:46.440 --> 01:40:49.650
sitting in the park, I
don't know, but I think

01:40:49.650 --> 01:40:52.269
that becomes a project
for all of us which is

01:40:52.269 --> 01:40:54.860
to not become enslaved by time,

01:40:54.860 --> 01:40:58.410
because it is the modern dilemma.

01:40:58.410 --> 01:41:00.680
- And can I just add
to this because I think

01:41:00.680 --> 01:41:03.150
that as we're thinking about
it, it just occurred to me

01:41:03.150 --> 01:41:08.150
that for me, it is the
creative act, feels timeless,

01:41:09.745 --> 01:41:14.745
intuition feels timeless and
it is, it comes in leaps,

01:41:15.090 --> 01:41:18.920
it's not that you build
towards it, sometimes you can

01:41:18.920 --> 01:41:21.820
create the conditions and not get there

01:41:21.820 --> 01:41:24.790
and sometimes you're washing
dishes and you have that

01:41:24.790 --> 01:41:28.580
moment of boom, almost
like a knowing and totality

01:41:28.580 --> 01:41:33.580
or something that just feels,
ah, it's as if this opens up.

01:41:34.750 --> 01:41:39.400
And so timeless, it has no measure,

01:41:39.400 --> 01:41:44.400
it more is an intensity
and I do think that I feel

01:41:44.436 --> 01:41:47.850
that that intensity can
happen at any moment.

01:41:47.850 --> 01:41:51.410
Sometimes it just doesn't
happen in an artist's residency

01:41:51.410 --> 01:41:54.550
of two months and
sometimes it really happens

01:41:54.550 --> 01:41:58.610
when I am petting my cat,
so when does it happen,

01:41:58.610 --> 01:42:02.110
when does that creative moment
happen, so that I would say

01:42:02.110 --> 01:42:03.383
is the timeless for me.

01:42:06.293 --> 01:42:11.293
- Up top in the middle here, there's, yep,

01:42:11.300 --> 01:42:14.683
right here in the middle, sorry,
bringing a microphone over.

01:42:17.360 --> 01:42:20.000
- My question follows
kind of along the lines of

01:42:20.000 --> 01:42:22.890
the gentleman earlier
about the astrophysicist,

01:42:22.890 --> 01:42:27.360
but an observation I have was
a lot of the presentations

01:42:27.360 --> 01:42:28.300
kind of

01:42:30.290 --> 01:42:35.290
saw time through kind of a
human perspective as a stage

01:42:35.640 --> 01:42:40.200
or a measuring tool to how we
organize or measure our lives

01:42:40.200 --> 01:42:43.740
or humanity, either our
personal interactions with

01:42:43.740 --> 01:42:46.040
our lives or

01:42:46.040 --> 01:42:50.883
how humanity organizes from
more the other side, again,

01:42:51.717 --> 01:42:53.633
as art, the lady said,

01:42:54.500 --> 01:42:57.770
humanity's just the very
end of the toilet paper roll

01:42:57.770 --> 01:43:02.770
but as time being the
whole entity of eternity,

01:43:05.490 --> 01:43:09.120
that's a separate perspective,

01:43:09.120 --> 01:43:12.550
I wonder if you have
anything to comment on

01:43:12.550 --> 01:43:15.480
the different types of time, like I said,

01:43:15.480 --> 01:43:17.721
we've been focusing more on the human,

01:43:17.721 --> 01:43:20.890
how do we use it, how do we organize it,

01:43:20.890 --> 01:43:25.890
in the greater realm, how
might that be looked at?

01:43:32.520 --> 01:43:34.070
- I can answer a little bit.

01:43:34.070 --> 01:43:36.490
I have, and I think that it's interesting

01:43:36.490 --> 01:43:38.610
because so much of my work is about time,

01:43:38.610 --> 01:43:41.160
so I have portraits of
mountains, for example,

01:43:41.160 --> 01:43:43.930
and I just set the camera
and sometimes it's like

01:43:43.930 --> 01:43:46.730
48 hours of a portrait of a mountain

01:43:46.730 --> 01:43:50.000
and so I think that to
me maybe that is still is

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:52.400
my point of view, and it's my eye

01:43:52.400 --> 01:43:55.960
but I am looking at more geological time

01:43:55.960 --> 01:43:58.280
or maybe atmospheric time, really, because

01:43:59.230 --> 01:44:01.580
nothing moved of the
mountain, but (laughs)

01:44:01.580 --> 01:44:02.580
the clouds did move.

01:44:04.760 --> 01:44:07.470
The bird, right, when I'm
looking at the arctic tern,

01:44:07.470 --> 01:44:09.780
a lot of the times it is
for me is animal time,

01:44:09.780 --> 01:44:12.300
I am actually trying to world with it

01:44:12.300 --> 01:44:16.130
and I'm camping with the bird, and I am,

01:44:16.130 --> 01:44:18.050
in order for me to film
it with the bollocks,

01:44:18.050 --> 01:44:20.900
I have to learn the
pattern because once I set

01:44:22.185 --> 01:44:24.950
the shutter speed, I cannot see anything,

01:44:24.950 --> 01:44:28.160
so I'm learning when is
it going to actually dive

01:44:28.160 --> 01:44:31.610
to go eat, so I think
that our times combine.

01:44:31.610 --> 01:44:34.887
And so for me I think that if anything,

01:44:34.887 --> 01:44:38.070
it's less my time and more its time,

01:44:38.070 --> 01:44:40.920
whatever I'm filming,
whatever I'm documenting,

01:44:40.920 --> 01:44:43.430
even the time of the
apparatus, I'm more interested

01:44:43.430 --> 01:44:45.806
in how the machine is
going to actually (clicks)

01:44:45.806 --> 01:44:47.013
do its thing.

01:44:48.210 --> 01:44:50.820
So I try to

01:44:50.820 --> 01:44:54.060
let go of my own time

01:44:54.060 --> 01:44:57.360
and there's times that
I've cried of exhaustion

01:44:57.360 --> 01:45:00.397
because there is nothing is happening,

01:45:00.397 --> 01:45:04.310
nothing further happens,
and I'm like (sobs)

01:45:04.310 --> 01:45:06.540
I'm running out of film, I can't do this,

01:45:06.540 --> 01:45:11.010
so it is something that I
am a slave of this time,

01:45:11.010 --> 01:45:16.010
other time, and I enjoy
that, being taken away

01:45:16.450 --> 01:45:20.463
and ripped out of my
humanity, if I could say.

01:45:23.068 --> 01:45:27.030
- I think I'm inspired by
women and men who have been

01:45:27.030 --> 01:45:32.030
looking at eternity, maybe
through a combination

01:45:33.110 --> 01:45:37.297
of art and science, better guide ways

01:45:39.082 --> 01:45:44.082
to begin to take in the
possibilities of eternity.

01:45:46.490 --> 01:45:50.423
And I can think of a number of artists,

01:45:50.423 --> 01:45:55.423
whether they're in music
or visual art, literature,

01:45:56.880 --> 01:45:59.600
but I really believe that

01:46:01.802 --> 01:46:06.320
the integration of the sciences

01:46:06.320 --> 01:46:09.500
with art is going to be

01:46:10.570 --> 01:46:12.630
a very important

01:46:14.170 --> 01:46:17.020
evolution for humanity,

01:46:17.020 --> 01:46:21.610
just how it comes together
in new ways to embrace

01:46:21.610 --> 01:46:24.593
the possibilities that exist of eternity.

01:46:25.490 --> 01:46:27.600
There's so much more
that we have to learn.

01:46:27.600 --> 01:46:29.593
We are such babes.

01:46:30.690 --> 01:46:33.880
You know, and particularly
when we begin to view

01:46:33.880 --> 01:46:38.880
eternity, it's like if I had my druthers,

01:46:39.070 --> 01:46:42.260
there's a huge part of
me that would have loved

01:46:42.260 --> 01:46:46.580
to have been an astrophysicist,
but there weren't many

01:46:46.580 --> 01:46:47.961
in my neighborhood.

01:46:47.961 --> 01:46:50.180
(audience laughs)

01:46:50.180 --> 01:46:51.013
But...

01:46:54.640 --> 01:46:55.530
I just...

01:46:56.810 --> 01:47:00.010
Because that's an important part,

01:47:00.010 --> 01:47:03.060
it's like I have to study physics more,

01:47:03.060 --> 01:47:06.860
to do the next projects
that I really want to do

01:47:06.860 --> 01:47:11.860
and it's finding the time
to approach that eternity

01:47:12.040 --> 01:47:14.240
and I really appreciate
you bringing that up

01:47:14.240 --> 01:47:18.010
because it's so important for you and I.

01:47:18.010 --> 01:47:21.760
- Thank you, and in that,
we're coming to the end

01:47:21.760 --> 01:47:25.790
of our time, I thought
maybe we could close,

01:47:25.790 --> 01:47:28.640
to see if any of you have
any closing statements,

01:47:28.640 --> 01:47:31.070
anything you'd like to
say that kind of tries to

01:47:31.070 --> 01:47:35.150
draw a thread between a few
of the points up to now,

01:47:35.150 --> 01:47:37.340
Asma, you were about to say something.

01:47:37.340 --> 01:47:40.390
- Actually, I was going to
just respond to that question,

01:47:40.390 --> 01:47:43.280
if I can do that instead
of a closing statement,

01:47:43.280 --> 01:47:45.170
that would be good,

01:47:45.170 --> 01:47:48.890
I mean, I think that not just
Islam but world religions

01:47:48.890 --> 01:47:52.166
do a great job of this, of unsettling

01:47:52.166 --> 01:47:55.290
human beings from their current perception

01:47:55.290 --> 01:47:58.560
and rigidness in time and
having them think about

01:47:58.560 --> 01:48:03.430
eternity and I mean, if
you look in the Koran,

01:48:03.430 --> 01:48:05.790
there are, and in Islamic literature,

01:48:05.790 --> 01:48:09.640
there are 25, 30 different words for time,

01:48:09.640 --> 01:48:12.420
measuring it in different
ways and talking about

01:48:12.420 --> 01:48:16.278
this idea of an eternity and
talking about what a day is,

01:48:16.278 --> 01:48:21.278
you know, in the eyes of God
and sort of the Old Testament

01:48:22.060 --> 01:48:24.100
and the New Testament and the Koran,

01:48:24.100 --> 01:48:29.100
the lifespans of certain
prophets, like what Moses lived,

01:48:29.240 --> 01:48:32.360
what, 900 years, I mean, I don't remember,

01:48:32.360 --> 01:48:36.870
but there's just this, I think
all of the world's religions

01:48:36.870 --> 01:48:41.870
constantly try to unsettle
sort of regular human

01:48:41.890 --> 01:48:45.750
perceptions of time and have
us think about eternity,

01:48:45.750 --> 01:48:48.770
pre eternity and then
extend our time horizons

01:48:50.200 --> 01:48:51.593
to an afterlife.

01:48:53.300 --> 01:48:56.263
- Thank you, Scott, Rebecca,
either of you, closing?

01:48:58.800 --> 01:49:01.630
- [Scott] Go ahead, you will
have something more interesting

01:49:01.630 --> 01:49:02.873
to say.
- No, no, no.

01:49:04.120 --> 01:49:06.480
But I have said so many
things, I will say it,

01:49:06.480 --> 01:49:09.253
but maybe after you. (laughs)

01:49:10.190 --> 01:49:11.753
All right, so then I'll go.

01:49:13.590 --> 01:49:18.590
I have collaborated with
geologists and with glaciologists,

01:49:18.910 --> 01:49:21.780
ornithologists, but it is something that

01:49:21.780 --> 01:49:25.003
for me, I agree, like one of my very,

01:49:25.890 --> 01:49:28.830
when I was young, when I
was about, I don't know,

01:49:28.830 --> 01:49:32.190
14 or so, I went to NASA,
and I wanted, I was sure

01:49:32.190 --> 01:49:33.740
I was going to be an astronaut.

01:49:34.660 --> 01:49:37.040
And because I continued to

01:49:37.040 --> 01:49:41.040
have that desire of expansion

01:49:41.040 --> 01:49:44.390
and just understanding
this sense of the universe

01:49:44.390 --> 01:49:49.190
extent and duration, not just the extent.

01:49:49.190 --> 01:49:52.070
So I know that I've been studying

01:49:52.070 --> 01:49:54.174
like (speaks foreign language)

01:49:54.174 --> 01:49:56.460
again, just the universe itself,
and it's just so amazing,

01:49:56.460 --> 01:50:00.920
the concept, when I feel
that I am kind of getting

01:50:00.920 --> 01:50:03.600
a sense of getting a little
bit lost, I just have that

01:50:03.600 --> 01:50:07.970
image of that universe and
the way in which we are trying

01:50:07.970 --> 01:50:11.150
to map that infinity
and it is so inspiring

01:50:11.150 --> 01:50:14.351
so for me it is like the
collaboration with science again,

01:50:14.351 --> 01:50:17.820
it inspires me, so much, so much

01:50:17.820 --> 01:50:20.080
and I feel that that's where

01:50:20.980 --> 01:50:23.170
I feel the...

01:50:24.320 --> 01:50:27.550
Both, and our relationship
to animals, for example,

01:50:27.550 --> 01:50:30.640
for me the post human, the
idea of that I do believe

01:50:30.640 --> 01:50:34.049
that our humanity's gonna
come from my relationship

01:50:34.049 --> 01:50:36.280
with wild animals, so that is another way

01:50:36.280 --> 01:50:39.940
of entering another universe,
so it's in one way very far

01:50:39.940 --> 01:50:42.620
and on the other hand is
like what is our humanity,

01:50:42.620 --> 01:50:47.293
'cause we have lost that
connection, we're very isolated.

01:50:48.820 --> 01:50:51.313
- Francisco Toledo.
- Si, claro.

01:50:52.310 --> 01:50:55.810
(speaks foreign language)

01:50:58.460 --> 01:51:00.354
- Scott, last words?

01:51:00.354 --> 01:51:02.560
(audience laughs)

01:51:02.560 --> 01:51:06.080
- Well, I guess what I
was trying to say was that

01:51:06.080 --> 01:51:08.390
the way we live today,
where our conception of time

01:51:08.390 --> 01:51:11.411
is a construct, and it's a
construct that's been imposed

01:51:11.411 --> 01:51:15.290
on us through a lot, many, many years,

01:51:15.290 --> 01:51:18.810
knowing that doesn't allow
us to deconstruct it,

01:51:18.810 --> 01:51:20.430
but knowing it does

01:51:22.110 --> 01:51:27.110
should free us to do projects
which either work against

01:51:27.110 --> 01:51:30.780
that construct or allow us
to escape that construct

01:51:30.780 --> 01:51:33.910
in different ways, and
I think that it's vital

01:51:33.910 --> 01:51:38.363
that we understand that we,
that our notion of modernity

01:51:38.363 --> 01:51:43.363
as it's been fashioned
through industry and factories

01:51:43.440 --> 01:51:44.870
and through a variety of other things,

01:51:44.870 --> 01:51:49.150
through stopwatches and
watches and trying to tell

01:51:49.150 --> 01:51:53.960
better time is a regime
which we brought on ourselves

01:51:53.960 --> 01:51:56.470
as humans, and that

01:51:57.570 --> 01:52:02.570
we're all as victims of
it, too busy, too harried,

01:52:02.905 --> 01:52:07.770
too stressed and we need
to understand that it is

01:52:07.770 --> 01:52:09.750
a regime we've brought on ourselves,

01:52:09.750 --> 01:52:12.090
it's not the regime of arctic terns,

01:52:12.090 --> 01:52:13.940
it's not the regime of rhythms,

01:52:13.940 --> 01:52:17.330
it's not the regime of
even the mechanical clocks

01:52:17.330 --> 01:52:21.650
of elephants, so I think it's
important to understand that

01:52:21.650 --> 01:52:24.510
and understand what it is
and understand the ways

01:52:24.510 --> 01:52:26.840
we get out of it into the moment.

01:52:26.840 --> 01:52:29.120
- Wonderful, thank you,
and everybody in the room,

01:52:29.120 --> 01:52:31.854
please join me in thanking our guests

01:52:31.854 --> 01:52:33.250
(audience applauds)

01:52:33.250 --> 01:52:37.339
for their time.

